Una breve historia de LiveJournal: uno de los pioneros de alojamiento de blogs
<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/fernand0/2697810299" title="Rusia"><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/3149/2697810299_e14f2bf524_m.jpg" width="240"  alt="Rusia" style="float:left; margin:5px"></a>
Un sitio del que no se suele hablar mucho (y menos en España) es <a href="https://www.livejournal.com/">LiveJournal</a>. Se trata de un alojamiento de blogs que está por ahí desde hace muchos años y que a pesar de que no se le nombra mucho ha tenido pocos problemas de censura (son -o solían ser- más o menos abiertos a diversos tipos de contenidos) y además sus sitios incluían algunas características 'sociales' cuando todavía todo eso estaba por inventar.
Por este motivo me gustó leer <a href="https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2019/01/the-linux-of-social-media-how-livejournal-pioneered-then-lost-web-blogging/">“The Linux of social media”—How LiveJournal pioneered (then lost) blogging</a>.

Nos recuerdan el sitio por el abandono de uno de sus bitacoreros notables, <a href="https://grrm.livejournal.com/">George R.R. Martin</a> que, aparentemente, decidió abrir su propia web.

<blockquote>
Last April, famed writer and hero-murderer George R.R. Martin announced that he was hoisting his ancient blog from his moldering LiveJournal onto his personal website. For casual Game of Thrones fans, it was a minor hiccup at best—most clicked the new link and never looked back. For a certain strata of enthusiasts, however, this was a far more momentous move.
</blockquote>

También los orígenes del sitio como un proyecto de dormitorio:

<blockquote>
Like many eventual household names in tech, LiveJournal started as a one-man project on a lark, driven by a techy teenager with too much time on his hands. As founder Brad Fitzpatrick recalls, in 1998, after getting kicked off America Online for messing with its service too much, he managed to convince a local ISP to enable his personal website to use the Common Gateway Interface protocol
</blockquote>

Su conversión en negocio, su crecimiento, problemas y final traslado del negocio a Rusia, donde era una de las plataformas más utilizadas

<blockquote>
...  had proven extremely popular in Russia since the platform’s launch—so much so that it became the country’s standardized word for “blog,” similar to Kleenex or Thermos. Eventually, all US employees were laid off in January 2009, and today LiveJournal continues on as a site run by Russians, for Russians.
</blockquote>

Interesante.

